<DESCRIPT>  PROFESSIONAL; BASEBALL; GAME; BRIEF  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  The Texas Rangers won their 13th consecutive game Sunday night, beating the
host Seattle Mariners 6-4 on run-scoring singles by Gary Pettis and Brian
Downing in the seventh inning.;    The Rangers' winning streak is the longest
in the major leagues since Oakland won 14 in a row in 1988. Texas' string is
the 31st streak of 13 or more victories in American League history.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  RANGERS MAKE IT 13 STRAIGHT  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  A.L. ROUNDUP  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Pettis, who hit a tie-breaking, two-run single in the 11th inning Saturday
night, again put the Rangers ahead. He had three of Texas' 14 hits.;    Mike
Stanley drew a one-out walk from Bill Swift (0-1) in the seventh, pinch hitter
Kevin Reimer singled with two out, and Pettis' RBI single gave Texas a 5-4
lead. Downing followed with an RBI single.;  ANGELS 6, BLUE JAYS 2: Mark
Langston won his fifth straight decision and Dave Winfield homered and moved
into 24th place on the all-time RBI list as California beat Toronto in
Anaheim.;    Langston (6-1) pitched a five-hitter and matched the longest
winning streak of his career, accomplished in 1986 with Seattle. He struck out
eight and walked two in his third complete game of the season.;  ROYALS 5,
TWINS 1: Brian McRae homered and singled twice as Kansas City defeated
Minnesota in Minneapolis.;    Bret Saberhagen (5-3) gave up eight hits in
winning his fourth consecutive decision. He walked two and struck out one.; 
TIGERS 9, RED SOX 4: Cecil Fielder, Rob Deer and Lou Whitaker each homered
during a five-run first inning as host Detroit clobbered Boston.;    Deer
homered for the third straight day and Mickey Tettleton also connected for
Detroit. The Tigers hit nine home runs in winning three times in the four-game
series.;  YANKEES 2, ORIOLES 1: Rookie Pat Kelly doubled home the tie-breaking
run in the 11th inning as visiting New York completed a sweep of Baltimore.; 
BREWERS 7, INDIANS 6: Greg Vaughn led off the 10th inning with his eighth home
run of the season to lift host Milwaukee past Cleveland.  </TEXT>
